The '''private security industry''' in [[South Africa]] is an industry providing guarding, monitoring, armed reaction, escorting, investigating and other security-related services to private individuals and companies in the country. Over the years there has been tremendous growth in the private security industry, not only in South Africa, but also in the rest of the world.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Recent Growth In The Private Security Industry {{!}} Building Security|url = http://www.buildingsecurity.com/recent-private-security-growth|website = www.buildingsecurity.com|accessdate = 2015-12-11}}</ref> The private security industry in South Africa is among the largest in the world,<ref>{{cite web|title=South Africa has world's largest private security industry; needs regulation – Mthethwa|url=http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=28306&Itemid=116|publisher=DefenceWeb|accessdate=3 May 2013}}</ref> with over 9,000 registered companies, 450,000 registered active private security guards and a further 1.5 million qualified (but inactive) guards; many times the available personnel than the combined South African police and army.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bigger than the army: South Africa's private security forces|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/02/08/business/south-africa-private-security|publisher=CNN|accessdate=3 May 2013}}</ref> Studies have shown that South Africa had 2.57 private security personnel for every police employee.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Does SA have the largest private security industry in the world?  - Africa Check|url = https://africacheck.org/reports/does-sa-have-the-largest-private-security-industry-in-the-world/|website = Africa Check|accessdate = 2015-12-11|language = en-US}}</ref> This is attributed by some to the country's relatively [[Crime in South Africa|high levels of crime]] to a lack of public funds from Parliament towards the [[South African Police Service]] (SAPS) or to an increasing trend in many countries towards government outsourcing of certain security functions.<ref>[http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2011/07/201177132021332490.html]</ref> Others have suggested the number of high-wealth individuals in South Africa in comparison with the rest of Africa has led to the growth of the industry. 

== Regulation ==
The private security industry in South Africa is regulated by the Private Security Industry Regulatory Authority, based in [[Centurion, Gauteng]]. The authority was established by the Private Security Industry Regulation Act 2001 and commenced operations in 2002. The authority has wide-ranging powers relating to the operation of private security companies in South Africa. Private security companies are required by law to be registered with the authority.

== 2006 private security strikes ==
[[Image:South Africa-2006-Security Guard Strike-001.jpg|thumb|Street violence occurred during the 2006 security strike.]]

In 2006, private security personnel went on [[Strike action|strike]] across South Africa. The strike lasted 96 days and cost the industry more than a million working days.<ref>{{cite book|last=http://www.labour.gov.za/downloads/documents/annual-reports/industrial-action-annual-report/2006/Annual Report - Industrial Action Report 2006 - Introduction.pdf|first=Industrial Action – Annual Report 2006|publisher=[[Department of Labour (South Africa)|Department of Labour]]|pages=2|isbn=978-0-9802645-6-2}}</ref> The strike was supported by the [[South African Transport and Allied Workers Union]] and 15 other trade unions.<ref>{{cite book|last=http://www.labour.gov.za/downloads/documents/annual-reports/industrial-action-annual-report/2006/Annual Report - Industrial Action Report 2006 - Introduction.pdf|first=Industrial Action – Annual Report 2006|publisher=[[Department of Labour (South Africa)|Department of Labour]]|pages=3|isbn=978-0-9802645-6-2}}</ref> The striking workers looted and damaged property, and committed violent crimes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=vn20060418014035460C703604|title=Shops looted as security strike continues |last=Schroeder |first=Fatima|date=18 April 2006|publisher=[[Cape Times]]|accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dfa.gov.za/docs/2006pq/pqp12.htm|title=Strike Actions of Security Workers – QUESTIONS TO THE PRESIDENT OF THE REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA|date=18 May 2006|publisher=[[Department of International Relations and Cooperation (South Africa)|Department of International Relations and Cooperation]]|accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref>

== Criticism ==
The Southern African Catholic Bishops' Conference criticised the private security industry in a 2012 briefing paper. The paper argued that the prevalence of private security in South Africa "perpetuates fear". The paper also noted that the private security industry "only protects the select	and privileged group that can afford to	pay for security services" and "exacerbates the	divide between the wealthy and the poor".<ref>http://www.cplo.org.za/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/BP-313-The-Private-Security-Industry-Dec-2012.pdf</ref>

